Bourne shell syntax is inspired by Algol 68¹, of which Bourne was a fan — the shell itself² was written in a highly idiosyncratic dialect of C, using the preprocessor to provide an Algol68ish syntax for control structures:<p><pre><code>    WHILE i--
    DO  t=trapcom[i];
        IF t==0 ORF *t
        THEN clrsig(i);
        FI
        trapflg[i]=0;
    OD
</code></pre>
The parser³ is straightforward recursive-descent in 400 lines including comments & blanks (the whole shell is about 4000 lines of code).<p>¹ <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ALGOL_68" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ALGOL_68</a><p>² <a href="http://minnie.tuhs.org/cgi-bin/utree.pl?file=V7/usr/src/cmd/sh" rel="nofollow">http://minnie.tuhs.org/cgi-bin/utree.pl?file=V7/usr/src/cmd/...</a><p>³ <a href="http://minnie.tuhs.org/cgi-bin/utree.pl?file=V7/usr/src/cmd/sh/cmd.c" rel="nofollow">http://minnie.tuhs.org/cgi-bin/utree.pl?file=V7/usr/src/cmd/...</a>

